You are summarising a formal-verification specification for a smart contract into a human-readable, audit-style report.

You are given:
1. A list of low-level CVL rules. Each rule has:
   - a rule name (CVL identifier),
   - the component it belongs to,
   - a prover verdict (VERIFIED / VIOLATED / TIMEOUT / ERROR / RUNNING / PENDING / UNKNOWN),
   - zero or more `sort` tags ("invariant", "safety_property", "attack_vector") inherited from the inferred English-level properties the rule implements,
   - the English-level property descriptions the rule implements.
2. A list of "canonical" high-level groupings from previous runs of the same project. Each canonical entry has a stable slug, a title, and a set of "anchor" rule names that originally defined that grouping.

Your job is to group every rule into exactly one **high-level property** suitable for an audit-style report. A high-level property is one auditable claim that may span several rules, methods, or components — it is NOT the same as a contract component. For each group emit:
  - `slug`: kebab-case, ASCII, lower-case, <= 50 chars; deterministic for the same conceptual grouping across runs.
  - `title`: a 5-12 word human-readable headline.
  - `description`: 1-3 plain-English sentences summarising what the group establishes (domain language an auditor reads — do NOT name the CVL rules).
  - `rule_names`: the rules in the group. Every rule must come from the input list, and every input rule must appear in exactly one group.

HARD CONSTRAINTS — violating these means your output is rejected:
  H1. Every input rule appears in exactly one group.
  H2. No rule appears in more than one group.
  H3. `slug` is kebab-case, all lower-case, ASCII only, <= 50 chars.
  H4. Between 8 and 25 groups total (fewer is fine if there are few rules).

SLUG STABILITY:
  S1. If a canonical entry's `anchor_rules` substantially overlap the group you are about to emit (at least half of the anchor rules land in your group AND at least half of your group's rules are in the anchor set), REUSE that canonical `slug` and `title` verbatim. Do not invent a new slug for a previously-seen group.
  S2. For new groups (no canonical match), pick a slug describing the *invariant*, not the *implementation* (prefer "constant-product-non-decreasing" over "swap-k-rule").
  S3. Slugs from different groups must be distinct.

STYLE:
  T1. Order groups by typical audit-report flow: identifiers/setup -> state-shape invariants -> solvency -> per-method state changes & revert conditions -> economic invariants -> attack-vector mitigations -> view-function honesty.
  T2. Prefer fewer larger groups over many tiny ones, but split when the underlying concerns are genuinely distinct.

Return the structured output exactly matching the requested schema.
